.TH "ONLINE" "1" "2026\-06\-11" "Winix" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
online \- block until the internet \(em or an endpoint \(em is actually
healthy
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]online\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]online\f[R] is a network\-readiness gate for scripts and agents.
It polls until every requested check passes, then exits 0.
Use it instead of writing your own poll loop.
.PP
By default (bare \f[B]online\f[R]), \f[B]\(eninternet\f[R] is implied: a
layered, captive\-portal\-aware check that confirms the internet is
actually usable, not merely that a network interface is up.
.PP
When multiple checks are requested (\f[B]\(eninternet\f[R] plus one or
more \f[B]\(enurl\f[R] checks), the gate opens only when \f[B]every\f[R]
check passes in the \f[B]same poll cycle\f[R].
.PP
The HTTP client does not follow redirects.
A captive portal\(cqs 302 redirect is therefore seen as a non\-204
response and correctly treated as \(lqnot online\(rq.
A \f[B]\(enurl\f[R] target that redirects will not match the
\f[B]2xx\f[R] default and will keep waiting \(em use \f[B]\-v\f[R] to
see the actual status returned.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\(eninternet\f[R]
Run a layered, captive\-portal\-aware internet check: (1) OS route check
(fast negative \(em no network traffic if the interface is down); (2)
DNS resolves the probe endpoint host; (3) HTTP GET returns status
\f[B]204 No Content\f[R] (a captive portal returns 200 or 302, never
204).
Default when no check flag is given.
.TP
\f[B]\(enurl\f[R] \f[I]URL\f[R]
Wait until \f[I]URL\f[R] returns a status matching \f[B]\(enstatus\f[R].
5xx responses, 429, connection failures, and non\-matching statuses all
cause the check to keep waiting.
Repeatable.
.TP
\f[B]\(enendpoint\f[R] \f[I]URL\f[R]
Override the built\-in 204 connectivity endpoints used by the internet
check.
Requires \f[B]\(eninternet\f[R].
Using \f[B]\(enendpoint\f[R] without \f[B]\(eninternet\f[R] (i.e.\ with
only \f[B]\(enurl\f[R] checks) is a usage error (exit 125).
Repeatable.
.TP
\f[B]\(enstatus\f[R] \f[I]SPEC\f[R]
Expected HTTP status for \f[B]\(enurl\f[R] checks.
Forms: \f[B]2xx\f[R] (any 2xx), comma\-separated list \f[B]200,204\f[R],
or range \f[B]200\-299\f[R].
Default: \f[B]2xx\f[R].
Using \f[B]\(enstatus\f[R] without \f[B]\(enurl\f[R] is a usage error
(exit 125).
.TP
\f[B]\(entimeout\f[R] \f[I]DURATION\f[R]
Total wait budget.
Accepts a number followed by a unit suffix: \f[B]ms\f[R] (milliseconds),
\f[B]s\f[R] (seconds), \f[B]m\f[R] (minutes).
\f[B]0\f[R] means wait forever.
Default: \f[B]10m\f[R].
On expiry the tool exits with code 124.
.TP
\f[B]\(eninterval\f[R] \f[I]DURATION\f[R]
Sleep between poll cycles.
Same duration format as \f[B]\(entimeout\f[R].
Default: \f[B]2s\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\(enprobe\-timeout\f[R] \f[I]DURATION\f[R]
Per\-probe DNS/HTTP timeout.
Same duration format as \f[B]\(entimeout\f[R].
Default: \f[B]3s\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\(enonce\f[R]
Run exactly one poll cycle and exit immediately.
Exit 0 if every check is healthy; exit 1 if any check fails.
Does not wait or retry.
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R], \f[B]\(enverbose\f[R]
Print per\-attempt diagnostics to stderr, including which checks passed
or failed and why.
.TP
\f[B]\(enjson\f[R]
Write the result envelope to stdout as JSON.
Human summary and verbose lines still go to stderr.
Fields: \f[B]tool\f[R], \f[B]version\f[R], \f[B]ready\f[R],
\f[B]timed_out\f[R], \f[B]elapsed_ms\f[R], \f[B]attempts\f[R],
\f[B]checks[]\f[R] (each check: \f[B]kind\f[R], \f[B]target\f[R],
\f[B]ok\f[R], \f[B]detail\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]\(encolor\f[R][=\f[I]WHEN\f[R]]
Coloured output: \f[B]auto\f[R] (default when omitted),
\f[B]always\f[R], or \f[B]never\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\(enno\-color\f[R]
